{"key":"processedPost-8553693","value":{"id":8553693,"first":8553270,"last":8554745,"when":1214234841,"utime":"06/23/08 06:27 PM","content":"You don't grow mushrooms on a 'casing', you grow them on the substrate.&nbsp; Any fruiting chamber you devise that will provide 95+ percent humidity and lots of air exchange will work great.<br />Cased substrates do NOT require a lower humidity and I always fail to know where people come up with such an idea.&nbsp; Primordia form in near saturation humidity, provided there's plenty of fresh air.&nbsp; <br />Personally, I prefer a mini-greenhouse for cased substrates, but if you're only using one or two trays, you can use a shotgun or any other terrarium design that provides humidity and air exchange.<br />RR","title":"Re: FC question"}}